questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;travel in train&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the second&amp;nbsp;part of the given sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;phrase&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;travel in train&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct phrase should be&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;travel by train&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;instead of&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;travel in train&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is because the preposition&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;by&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is used when referring to a mode of transportation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;They decided to travel by train instead of driving to New Delhi.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;They decided to &lt;strong&gt;travel by train&lt;/strong&gt; instead of driving to New Delhi.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the &lt;strong&gt;subjects are both singular&lt;/strong&gt; and are &lt;strong&gt;connected by&lt;/strong&gt; the words &lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;not/but, not,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;or, nor, neither/nor, either/or,&amp;nbsp;not only/but also, etc&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot; the &lt;strong&gt;verb is singular&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;/span&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Either Sita or Geeta is&lt;/strong&gt; to blame for the accident&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the &lt;strong&gt;subjects are both plurals&lt;/strong&gt; and are &lt;strong&gt;connected by&lt;/strong&gt; the words &lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;not/but, not,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;or, nor, neither/nor, either/or,&amp;nbsp;not only/but also, etc&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot; the &lt;strong&gt;verb is plural&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Not only dogs but also cats are&lt;/strong&gt; available at the&amp;nbsp;shelter&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;being finished&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;https://cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The part &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;being finished&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is in passive voice.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It indicates that the subject receives the action &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;to be finished.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;But, the subject here is implied.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Moreover, the implied subject &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;you&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; performs the action &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;to finish&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; against the object &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;the last chapter of the book.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This part should be replaced with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;finishing.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the correct answer&amp;nbsp;is&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;being finished.&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​​The c&lt;u&gt;orrect sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;After &lt;strong&gt;finishing&lt;/strong&gt; the last chapter of the book, return it to her.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;​&lt;img height=&quot;41px&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/21/08/new_16299572932401.png&quot; style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot; width=&quot;280px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;font color=&quot;#3b3e4d&quot;&gt;The meaning of the word&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;return&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;to come or go back to a place.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/span&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;I leave on 10 July and &lt;strong&gt;return&lt;/strong&gt; on 6 August.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;https://cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hinglish-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hinglish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;पार्ट &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;being finished&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; निष्क्रिय आवाज में है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;यह इंगित करता है कि subject,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;to be finished&amp;#39;,&lt;/span&gt; action प्राप्त करता है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;लेकिन, यहां subject निहित है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इसके अलावा, निहित subject &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;you&amp;#39;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;object &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;the last chapter of the book&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; के खिलाफ &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;to finish&amp;#39;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;action करता है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इस भाग को &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;finishing&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; से बदल दिया जाना चाहिए।&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect verb form &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;have&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; used with the singular noun &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Mountain biking&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Singular subjects require singular verbs.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Mountain biking has&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; ensuring subject-verb agreement.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 4&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Mountain biking &lt;/strong&gt;has always attracted non-conformists and strong personalities.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1: &amp;quot;always attracted non-conformists,&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2: &amp;quot;No error&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This would be the correct option if there were no mistakes in the sentence, but there is an error in part 4.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;3: &amp;quot;and strong personalities.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The erroneous part of the sentence is:&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;than I&amp;rsquo;m not surprised&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Replace&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;than&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot; with &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;then&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot; to correct the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;than&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is used to compare things.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;then&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; means &amp;quot;at that time&amp;quot; and is used to talk about when things will happen.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The conditional &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;if&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; plays a role of a subordinating conjunction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;If...then&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is called correlative conjunction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Correlative conjunctions are conjunctions used to illustrate how two words or phrases within a sentence relate to each other.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In such sentences &amp;quot;if&amp;quot; is used in the first action and &amp;quot;then&amp;quot; is used as a consequence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2&lt;/span&gt;, which contains an error in it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Corrected sentence:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;If that is the case then I&amp;rsquo;m not surprised by&amp;nbsp;what&amp;rsquo;s happening.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;He was most careful while stealing the crown jewels.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;carefullest&amp;quot; is not a correct superlative form in English.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English, adjectives with two or more syllables typically form the comparative with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;more&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; and the superlative with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;most&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, &amp;quot;careful&amp;quot; should form its superlative as &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;most careful&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence should use &amp;quot;most careful&amp;quot; to correctly convey the highest degree of carefulness.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 4&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;He was most careful while stealing the crown jewels&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;He was carefully while stealing the crown jewels.&amp;quot; &amp;ndash; This option uses the adverb&amp;nbsp;instead of the superlative form. Hence, the option is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2:&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;He was most carefuller while stealing the crown jewels.&amp;quot; &amp;ndash; This option incorrectly combines both the superlative &amp;quot;most&amp;quot; and the comparative &amp;quot;carefuller&amp;quot;, which is grammatically incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;He was carefuller while stealing the crown jewels.&amp;quot; &amp;ndash; This option uses &amp;quot;carefuller&amp;quot; which is not a correct comparative form in English. The correct comparative form is &amp;quot;more careful&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;A&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in &lt;strong&gt;part &amp;#39;A&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; of the &lt;strong&gt;sentence&lt;/strong&gt; because &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;participation&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is used instead of &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;participate&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;sentence&lt;/strong&gt; is talking about the opportunity to participate in fair and free elections, which is an action and not a state of being.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore the &lt;strong&gt;verb &amp;#39;participate&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; should be used instead of &lt;strong&gt;noun&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;participation&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;, which means &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;take part in an action or endeavour&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;option 1&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; is the correct answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;: &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The opportunity to participate in fair and free elections &lt;/strong&gt;and hold public office should be viewed as a fundamental right of every citizen.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Many historians argues that&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The error lies in the subject-verb agreement. &amp;quot;Historians&amp;quot; is a plural noun, so the verb &amp;quot;argues&amp;quot; should be &amp;quot;argue.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;The presence of &amp;quot;s&amp;quot; in &amp;quot;argues&amp;quot; indicates a singular subject, making it incorrect with the plural subject &amp;quot;historians.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Correcting &amp;quot;argues&amp;quot; to &amp;quot;argue&amp;quot; aligns the verb with the plural subject.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Such errors are common when the subject&amp;#39;s plurality is not matched by the verb, leading to grammatical inconsistency.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is- Correct answer Option 1.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Option 2 &amp;amp; 3: Both are correctly constructed, effectively presenting the claim without grammatical errors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li role=&quot;presentation&quot;&gt;Option 4: This was not the correct choice, as there was a clear grammatical error in option A.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;(a); i.e. this part contains an error&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Poors&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; in part&lt;strong&gt; (a)&lt;/strong&gt; should be replaced with &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the poor&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Poor &lt;/strong&gt;is an &lt;strong&gt;adjective &lt;/strong&gt;and adjectives &lt;strong&gt;don&amp;#39;t have plural form&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We sometimes use it &lt;strong&gt;as a noun to represent a whole group of people&lt;/strong&gt;. In that case, it&amp;#39;s form is fixed; i.e. &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the poor&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The poor (plural noun)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;poor people considered together as a group
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ex: &lt;strong&gt;The poor &lt;/strong&gt;go hungry while &lt;u&gt;the rich&lt;/u&gt; eat cake&lt;/em&gt;. (&lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;the rich&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/em&gt; is a similar case)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;Therefore, the correct sentence is&lt;/u&gt;: &lt;em&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The poor&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; are always exploited in this world&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;greatly&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; before the term &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;truths&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &amp;quot;greatly&amp;quot; is an adverb, whereas an adjective is needed to modify the noun &amp;quot;truths&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;great truths in life&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 3&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The &lt;strong&gt;great truths &lt;/strong&gt;in life are usually the most unpleasant to hear.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;1: &amp;quot;are usually the,&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;2: &amp;quot;most unpleasant to hear.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;4: &amp;quot;No error&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This would be the correct option if there were no mistakes in the sentence, but there is an error in part 3.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;No error&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;helping of&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;means&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;the amount of it that you get in a single serving&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;She gave them extra &lt;strong&gt;helpings&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;of&lt;/strong&gt; ice cream.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the use of &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;helping of&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; here is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;And rest of the sentence follows all the &lt;strong&gt;grammatical rules.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Mrs. Verma refused the second helping of ice cream.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;C&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;this part of the sentence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;has an error&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the third&amp;nbsp;part of the given sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;phrase&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;to help you&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct phrase should be&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;looking forward to helping you&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;because&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;to&amp;#39; is a preposition&lt;/strong&gt; here, and it should be followed by a gerund (verb + ing).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;looking forward to&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is used, it is always followed by a gerund.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the correct phrase should be&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;to helping you&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;instead of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;to help you&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 3&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;They are looking forward to helping you&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1 (A):&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;There is no error in the first part of the sentence, &amp;#39;They are.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2 (B):&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;There is no error in the second part of the sentence, &amp;#39;looking forward.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4 (D):&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;This option indicates there is no error in the sentence, which is incorrect as there is an error in part C.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Option 3&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;will prevent the hand sanitizer of&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the context of this sentence, the preposition &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;of&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;correct phrase&lt;/strong&gt; should be &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;prevent the hand sanitizer from drying out your skin.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In English,&lt;/strong&gt; when you want to express that you are preventing something from happening, the preposition&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;from&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is used.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;This is a collocation&lt;/strong&gt; - a common combination of words in a language - and it&amp;#39;s simply how it&amp;#39;s expressed in English.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the&lt;strong&gt; correct sentence &lt;/strong&gt;is: &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;Adding aloe vera gel will prevent the hand sanitizer from drying out your skin.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;No sooner had the first rays of dawn pierced through the horizon when&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;No sooner had&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is used to show that one action happens immediately after another. It&amp;#39;s followed by &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;than&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to &lt;strong&gt;link&lt;/strong&gt; the &lt;strong&gt;two events.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;However, the error lies in using &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;when&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; after &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;No sooner had the first rays of dawn pierced through the horizon.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt; The correct structure requires &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;than&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; to maintain the correct &lt;strong&gt;sequence of events.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The revised sentence reads:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;No sooner had the first rays of dawn pierced through the horizon than &lt;/strong&gt;the bustling city came alive with the symphony of honking cars, chirping birds, and hurried footsteps, ushering in a new day filled with endless possibilities and bustling activity that characterized urban life.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This correction maintains the &lt;strong&gt;proper grammar structure, &lt;/strong&gt;emphasizing the immediate succession of events by using &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;than&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; after the initial clause.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Part B is the correct answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Use &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;has known&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39; instead of &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;been knowing&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;RULE&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Non action verb&lt;/span&gt;s can&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;not&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;be expressed in &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Continuous/Progressive Tense&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;NON ACTION VERBS&lt;/span&gt;:-
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;taste, feel, smell, sound, seem, sense, love, hate, like, dislike, belong, own, have, possess, look, appear, mean, fit, resemble, prefer, &lt;strong&gt;know&lt;/strong&gt;, suppose&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;etc&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;have&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is used as a &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;non action verb&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39; hence it can&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;not&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;be used in &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;continuous tens&lt;/span&gt;e&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;After converting the sentence given in &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;present perfect continuous&amp;#39; tense into &amp;#39;present perfect&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39;, the correct sentence will be-
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;He &lt;strong&gt;has known &lt;/strong&gt;me since 2019.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
		&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/confusion-points-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confusion Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is important to understand that a verb can act as both - &amp;quot;action verb &amp;amp; non action verb&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It depends on the usage of it. Go through the below examples to understand this confusion&amp;nbsp;point:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;ol style=&quot; margin-left: 40px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;I&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;am having&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;my lunch. (&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct in Present Continuous&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;tense because verb &amp;#39;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;have&lt;/span&gt;&amp;#39; is used as an&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;action&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;verb)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;I&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;am having&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;two kids.&amp;nbsp;(&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Incorrect in Present Continuous&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;tense because verb &amp;#39;&lt;b&gt;have&lt;/b&gt;&amp;#39; is used as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Non action&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;verb)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;I&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;have&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;two kids. (&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct&lt;/span&gt;)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

