The students were diligently / studying for their exams / for weeks before you arrived.

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Than &lt;/strong&gt;should be replaced by &lt;strong&gt;to&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Than&lt;/strong&gt; is used with &lt;strong&gt;a comparative degree of adjectives i&lt;/strong&gt;n order to make a comparison between two things or persons.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Superior is also a&lt;strong&gt; comparative degree&lt;/strong&gt; but it is followed by&lt;strong&gt; the preposition to&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The meaning of superior is &lt;strong&gt;more than&lt;/strong&gt;. Hence, the use of &lt;strong&gt;than is redundant&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the part that contains a grammatical error is&lt;strong&gt; than Reeta&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect usage of the present perfect continuous tense &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;has been teaching&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; when referring to a future point in time.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;correct tense&lt;/strong&gt; to use in this context is the future perfect tense.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;will have been teaching&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 1&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;By the time she retires, she &lt;strong&gt;will have been teaching&lt;/strong&gt; at the university for 30 years.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;By the time she retires,&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;at the university for 30 years&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;No error&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This would be the correct option if there were no mistakes in the sentence, but there is an error in part 1.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, the erroneous part is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;little did him know that the results will come out worse than expected.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Objective pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;him&amp;#39; should be replaced by&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;subjective pronoun &amp;#39;he&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example of Objective pronoun:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Take a picture of &lt;strong&gt;him&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;(Here &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;him&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is an objective pronoun)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example of Subjective pronoun:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You&lt;/strong&gt; have some ice cream.(&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;Here &amp;#39;you&amp;#39; is a Subjective pronoun)&lt;br /&gt;
		&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​Correct sentence:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;When Sanathan asked Mr. Jignesh for a fresh evaluation of his performance in the last financial year, little did&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;he&lt;/u&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;know that the results will come out worse than expected.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;The following sentence has been divided into parts. One of them may contain an&amp;nbsp;error. Select the part that contains the error from the given options. If you don&amp;rsquo;t find&amp;nbsp;any error, mark &amp;lsquo;No error&amp;rsquo; as your answer.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I was very lucky (A)/ that day and catched (B)/ a lot of fish. (C)/ no error(D)

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;​that day and catched&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the use of the incorrect &lt;strong&gt;past tense form&lt;/strong&gt; of the &lt;strong&gt;verb&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;catch&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; The correct &lt;strong&gt;past tense &lt;/strong&gt;form of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;catch&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;caught&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; not &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;catched&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here&amp;#39;s a more detailed explanation:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;catch&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is &lt;strong&gt;irregular&lt;/strong&gt;, which means it doesn&amp;#39;t follow the standard rule for forming past tense verbs by adding &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;-ed&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;to &lt;strong&gt;the base form. &lt;/strong&gt;Instead, &lt;strong&gt;its past tense form&lt;/strong&gt; is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;caught&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; For instance:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Present tense: I catch a fish every morning.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Past tense: Yesterday, I caught three fish at the lake&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence sentence, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;catched&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is incorrectly used as &lt;strong&gt;the past tense&lt;/strong&gt; of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;catch&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; The correct form is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;caught&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; So the corrected sentence should be: &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;I was very lucky that day and &lt;strong&gt;caught&lt;/strong&gt; a lot of fish.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using the correct&lt;strong&gt; past tense form &lt;/strong&gt;is crucial for maintaining grammatical accuracy in sentences.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;​Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;I was very lucky &lt;strong&gt;that day and caught&lt;/strong&gt; a lot&amp;nbsp;of fish.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The erroneous part is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;option 1), i.e., &amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;will give his consent&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The error lies in the part &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;will give his consent&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;According to the rules of grammar, conditional sentences describe a situation that must exist before something else can happen.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;Words like &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;unless, until, when, as soon as, before, after&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; are used to denote the time clause in conditional sentences.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;Here we should not&amp;nbsp;use the simple future tense in the time clause, but&amp;nbsp;we should&amp;nbsp;use the &lt;strong&gt;simple present tense.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;In the given sentence,&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;as soon as&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is followed by the time clause.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;Therefore i&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;n the given sentence, we need to &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;use the simple present tense &amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;gives his consent&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;in place of the simple future tense&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt; &amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;will give his consent&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to make the sentence grammatically correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;Hence, &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the correct answer is option&amp;nbsp;1.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;They will leave for Delhi as soon as their father&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;gives his consent.&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect preposition &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;on&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; used before the time &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;6 a.m.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;When specifying the time, the correct preposition to use is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;at,&amp;quot; not &amp;quot;on.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;at 6 a.m.,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The Shatabdi Express arrives &lt;strong&gt;at 6 a.m.&lt;/strong&gt; in the morning.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: &amp;quot;in the morning.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: &amp;quot;Express arrives&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;The Shatabdi&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; Option 4) &amp;quot;through hand.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The error lies in the prepositional phrase&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;through hand,&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; which is not the correct idiomatic expression for indicating direct delivery by a person.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;correct phrase&lt;/strong&gt; should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;by hand,&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; which means delivering something personally rather than through mechanical or electronic means.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;So, the &lt;strong&gt;corrected part &lt;/strong&gt;of the sentence would be &amp;quot;by hand, door to door,&amp;quot; describing how the postman delivers the letters personally from one door to another.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is-&lt;strong&gt; 4) through hand.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;I found that I had given a pair&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The issue lies in the segment &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;I had given a pair of adorable kittens.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt; This&lt;strong&gt; construction implies&lt;/strong&gt; that&lt;strong&gt; the speaker was the one performing the action of giving the kittens&lt;/strong&gt;. However, based on the context, the intended meaning is that the&lt;strong&gt; speaker received the kittens as a surprise gift.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correction involves &lt;strong&gt;adjusting the verb form to reflect&lt;/strong&gt; that the action of receiving occurred. The corrected phrase is: &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;I had been given a pair of adorable kittens.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here&amp;#39;s the breakdown:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;I had been given&amp;quot;: &lt;/strong&gt;This construction uses &lt;strong&gt;the past perfect tense&lt;/strong&gt; in the passive voice. &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Had been given&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; indicates that the speaker was the recipient of the action (receiving the kittens). The &lt;strong&gt;passive voice emphasizes the action &lt;/strong&gt;received rather than performed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Had&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; as &lt;strong&gt;the auxiliary verb for past perfect&lt;/strong&gt;: It places the action (receiving) in the past before another action (finding the kittens at home).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Been given&amp;quot;:&lt;/strong&gt; This is the &lt;strong&gt;past participle &lt;/strong&gt;of the verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;give&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; in the passive voice. It emphasizes that the speaker was the recipient of the gift (kittens) rather than the one performing the action of giving.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the corrected sentence grammatically signifies that the speaker arrived home and discovered that someone else had given them a pair of adorable kittens as a surprise gift, aligning with the intended meaning.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Upon arriving home from a tiring day at work, &lt;strong&gt;I found that I had been given a pair&lt;/strong&gt; of adorable kittens as a surprise gift.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The error is in&lt;strong&gt; part (c) &lt;/strong&gt;of the sentence.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct preposition to use is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;in&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; instead of &amp;quot;on.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The preposition &amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: bolder;&quot;&gt;in&lt;/span&gt;&amp;quot; is used to indicate a specific year, so it is appropriate to use &amp;quot;in 1492&amp;quot; to specify the time when Columbus made his first voyage.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The corrected sentence would be: &lt;strong&gt;(a) Columbus made his (b) first voyage from Europe to America (c) in 1492.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;The breathtaking sceneries of&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence has an error in the word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;sceneries&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; The correct form should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;scenery&amp;quot; (singular), not &amp;quot;sceneries&amp;quot; (plural).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The corrected sentence would be:&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;The breathtaking scenery of &lt;/strong&gt;the mountains and lakes left us in awe during our hike through the national park.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Scenery&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is &lt;strong&gt;a mass noun, &lt;/strong&gt;meaning it doesn&amp;#39;t typically have &lt;strong&gt;a plural form.&lt;/strong&gt; It refers to the overall visual aspects of a landscape or view, encompassing natural features such as mountains, lakes, forests, and so on. It&amp;#39;s &lt;strong&gt;an uncountable noun used&lt;/strong&gt; to describe &lt;strong&gt;the collective visual impression of an area.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;For example:&lt;/em&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The coastal scenery in that region is stunning.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The rural scenery in the countryside was serene and picturesque.&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the corrected sentence, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;scenery&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is used to describe &lt;strong&gt;the combined visual beauty of mountains and lakes,&lt;/strong&gt; and it remains &lt;strong&gt;singular&lt;/strong&gt; because it represents the overall landscape or view, not individual components.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other nouns which are always used in singular form: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Scenery, information, furniture, advice, machinery, stationery, news, poetry, business, mischief, fuel, issue, repair, bedding.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
